going forward, except in some limited cases (for example, some teams have special configuration for PowerShell cmdlets that only generate cmdlets for some of their OpenApi specs).  Generally though, this should not be a concern.
Tag name changes:  tags can affect Terraform.  You can use the @tag decorator (typespec core) to ensure that any missing tags are added to the spec
doc/summary:  The way the converter does this maximizes the usefulness of summary/description for client sdks.  You can still add summary documentation for other consumers of the specs using the @summary decorator

For one thing. the most important thing for the spec is that is accurately represents the API.  There is client decoration available in many cases to keep the sdk from breaking as we make sure the API is accurate:
x-ms-skip-url-encoding:  Parameters like 'scope'  and 'resourceUri'  generally contain multiple path segments.  If they occur in a path parameter, you almost always want those path segments included in the path, so skipping url; encoding is appropriate.  If they occur in query parameters, then url encoding is irrelevant.  You can specificall set url encoding for path parameters by decorating with @path(#{allowReserved: true})
The value array.  Generally, the Value array occurs in list types, which also have a nextLink.  No more properties should mean no more nextLink.  It is almost always the case in actual practice that value always occurs in list responses, and this was a piece of inaccurate variance in the original spec.  The best practice is to validate that your service can have a response that does not contain a value property (which is unlikely), and only change the response type then.  Whether or not this is the case, it is highly unlikely to have any impact on clients, which have standard mechaniisms for handling paged types.
Single OpenAPI file:  Teams no longer maintain the OpenAPI spec, they maintain the TypeSpec as the source of truth and OpenApi is generated from that, so the layout of the OpenAPI files should not be important going forward, except in some limited cases (for example, some teams have special configuration for PowerShell cmdlets that only generate cmdlets for some of their OpenApi specs).  Generally though, this should not be a concern.
